{ 
    Mica UTF-8 Source Code and UTF-32 String Literals Example

    This example demonstrates Mica's full Unicode support, showcasing one of its most impressive features:
    you can write source code using any language or script that UTF-8 supports!

    Key Concepts Covered:

    1. UTF-8 SOURCE CODE SUPPORT
       - Variable names can use any Unicode characters (Chinese, Arabic, Greek, Japanese, etc.)
       - Procedure names can be written in any language
       - Comments can contain any Unicode text
       - Enables truly international programming - write code in YOUR native language!

    2. UTF-32 STRING LITERALS
       - Strings are stored internally as UTF-32 (full Unicode support)
       - Can contain emojis, mathematical symbols, ancient scripts, and more
       - No character encoding issues - everything "just works"
       - Use %ls format specifier for UTF-32 string output

    3. MULTILINGUAL IDENTIFIERS
       - Examples from 7+ languages: German, Ukrainian, Greek, Japanese, Russian, Chinese, Korean
       - Same variable can be meaningful in different languages
       - Demonstrates true internationalization of programming

    4. CULTURAL DIVERSITY
       - Right-to-left scripts (Arabic)
       - Logographic systems (Chinese, Japanese)
       - Alphabetic scripts (Latin, Cyrillic, Greek)
       - Syllabic scripts (Korean Hangul)
       - All work seamlessly together in one program!

    5. EMOJI AND SYMBOLS
       - Full emoji support in strings and comments
       - Mathematical symbols, currency symbols, flags
       - Creates expressive and visually rich output

    This example demonstrates that programming doesn't have to be limited to English. 
    Mica embraces global diversity and makes coding accessible to everyone, regardless of their native language or script.
}
